const e="ITR-5",i="ITR-5",t="2025-26",s="2026-27",o="Income Tax Return for partnership firms, LLPs, AOPs, BOIs, cooperative societies, and local authorities",a="ITR-5 is filed by entities that are not individuals, HUFs, or companies. It covers partnership firms (registered and unregistered), Limited Liability Partnerships (LLPs), Association of Persons (AOPs), Body of Individuals (BOIs), local authorities, cooperative societies, and artificial juridical persons. These entities maintain books of accounts and file comprehensive returns including Profit & Loss statements, Balance Sheets, and schedules for partner/member capital accounts and profit allocation. Firms and LLPs are taxed at a flat rate of 30% on total income (plus surcharge at 12% if income exceeds ₹1 crore) plus 4% Health and Education Cess.",n="No upper limit",r=["Partnership Firm (Registered)","Partnership Firm (Unregistered)","Limited Liability Partnership (LLP)","Association of Persons (AOP)","Body of Individuals (BOI)","Local Authority","Cooperative Society","Artificial Juridical Person","Estate of deceased person","Estate of insolvent person"],c=[{id:"EC1",criterion:"Partnership Firms",detail:"All partnership firms – registered (u/s 59 of Partnership Act 1932) and unregistered – must file ITR-5. Registered firms can claim deductions u/s 40(b) for salary/interest to partners. Unregistered firms cannot claim these deductions.",isInclusion:!0},{id:"EC2",criterion:"Limited Liability Partnerships",detail:"LLPs incorporated under the LLP Act 2008 file ITR-5. LLPs are treated as firms for income tax purposes and taxed at 30% flat rate. Partners' share of profit from LLP is exempt in partners' hands u/s 10(2A).",isInclusion:!0},{id:"EC3",criterion:"Association of Persons (AOP)",detail:"Group of persons who join together for a common purpose. Income is taxed at the rate applicable to members or at maximum marginal rate, unless members' shares are determinate.",isInclusion:!0},{id:"EC4",criterion:"Body of Individuals (BOI)",detail:"Similar to AOP but consists only of individuals (not companies or firms). BOIs that own property jointly and earn income file ITR-5.",isInclusion:!0},{id:"EC5",criterion:"Cooperative Societies",detail:"Cooperative societies registered under State Acts or Central Act. Special tax rates apply u/s 115BAD (new regime at 22%) or normal slab rates with deductions u/s 80P.",isInclusion:!0},{id:"EC6",criterion:"Local Authorities",detail:"Municipalities, panchayats, and other local authorities file ITR-5 for income from commercial activities.",isInclusion:!0}],l=[{id:"EX1",criterion:"Companies",detail:"Private limited, public limited, one person company (OPC), foreign companies must file ITR-6 (or ITR-7 if claiming exemption u/s 11). LLPs are NOT companies – they file ITR-5.",consequence:"Wrong form. Company filing ITR-5 renders return defective."},{id:"EX2",criterion:"Charitable Trusts and Religious Institutions",detail:"Trusts, societies, and institutions claiming exemption u/s 11 or 10(23C) must file ITR-7. If not claiming exemption, they file ITR-5 or ITR-6 depending on entity type.",consequence:"If trust files ITR-5 instead of ITR-7, exemption u/s 11 cannot be claimed."},{id:"EX3",criterion:"Individuals and HUFs",detail:"ITR-5 is only for the listed entity types. Individual partners file ITR-3 (or ITR-2) for their personal income.",consequence:"Wrong assessee type."}],d=!1,p=["Misconception: LLPs should file ITR-6 like companies. Fact: LLPs are taxed like partnership firms and file ITR-5.","Misconception: Partners' share of profit from firm is taxable in ITR-5. Fact: Partners' share of profit is allowed as deduction to firm u/s 40(b) and is exempt in partners' hands u/s 10(2A). The firm is taxed on its net income after such deductions.","Misconception: Unregistered firms pay higher tax. Fact: Tax rate is the same (30% flat), but unregistered firms cannot deduct salary/interest to partners u/s 40(b).","Misconception: AOP and BOI are the same. Fact: BOI comprises only individuals; AOP can include companies and other entities.","Misconception: Cooperative societies pay the same tax as firms. Fact: Cooperative societies have special provisions including 80P deduction and option for 22% rate u/s 115BAD.","Misconception: LLP partners' remuneration has no cap. Fact: LLP partners' remuneration is also governed by Section 40(b) limits same as partnership firms."],m=["Section 194T (effective 1 April 2024): Firms and LLPs must deduct TDS at 10% on salary, remuneration, commission, bonus, and interest paid to partners if aggregate exceeds ₹20,000 per year. This is a major compliance addition for all partnership firms and LLPs.","Section 43B(h) – MSME Payment Disallowance: Applies to all assessee types including firms. Payments to MSME suppliers outstanding beyond 45-day credit period disallowed until actual payment.","Section 115BAD for cooperative societies: Cooperative societies can opt for 22% flat tax rate under 115BAD (no surcharge) from FY 2020-21 onwards. Once opted, cannot switch back.","AMT at 18.5% applies to LLPs/firms when they claim certain deductions (80-IA, 80-IB, 10AA etc.) and their adjusted total income exceeds ₹20 lakh.","Partner remuneration u/s 40(b): Book profit definition and allowable remuneration unchanged. Salary paid to working partners limited to ₹3 lakh or 90% of book profit up to ₹6 lakh, then 60% of balance book profit.","Capital gains rates: LTCG on equity u/s 112A at 12.5% (above ₹1.25 lakh exemption), STCG u/s 111A at 20% – applicable to firm investment portfolios as well."],u="https://www.incometax.gov.in/iec/foportal/downloads/form-itr-5",f={formId:e,popularName:i,fyApplicable:t,ayApplicable:s,shortDescription:o,longDescription:a,incomeLimitTotal:n,assesseeTypes:r,eligibilityCriteria:c,exclusionCriteria:l,hufApplicable:d,commonMisconceptions:p,fy202526Changes:m,officialFormLink:u};export{r as assesseeTypes,s as ayApplicable,p as commonMisconceptions,f as default,c as eligibilityCriteria,l as exclusionCriteria,e as formId,m as fy202526Changes,t as fyApplicable,d as hufApplicable,n as incomeLimitTotal,a as longDescription,u as officialFormLink,i as popularName,o as shortDescription};
